The first virtual operator is already coming to the Czech Republic this year.
Probably.
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite developed and our operators offer almost all services as their partners in Western Europe.
However, here we still lack something - the virtual operator, who would force those to be cheaper.
Probably won't be long to get there.
That the Czech operators are part of the most expensive in Europe, we have already written it on mobile.cz.
The rest also confirmed this by the Czech Telecommunications Office (ČTú) which warned that the price of SMS messages in our country is of the most expensive in the Union.
After the last steps of the European Commission in the field of regulating roaming fees, it is likely to reach a paradoxical situation - for some customers of Czech mobile operators, SMS sending from abroad will be cheaper than if sent from home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic remain so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, lack of competition that really wants to fight.
This is probably paradoxical, because we have three mobile networks and their high coverage is more than 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to regret that there is an extreme competition in the Czech market.
The President of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office (ČTú), Pavel Dvořák, has already said that there is no place in the Czech Republic for any other operator.
It is perhaps true that for a classic operator with his own network he no longer has too many possibilities (for the rest, it would be quite difficult to find some frequency).
However, there is still a possibility - the virtual operator.
Precisely the entry of the virtual operator into the mobile telephony market brought a significant drop in prices before which classical operators also had to react.
At the same time, even before the entry of sharks such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile to the Britain market, voices similar to here and there were heard.
It has been shown that there is room for this type of operator and that they can be successful.
On the other hand, there is no need to look for too far-reaching examples.
In February of this year we informed you about the premiere of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
Only after half a year, this operator managed to get over 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest operator in the neighbouring country.
On the other hand, after Mobilking is the Penta group which, apart from that, in the Czech Republic is the owner of U:fon.
The advantage of virtual operators is the possibility of focusing on many more specific target groups.
In addition, to enable them to function effectively, it is enough for many less customers than a classic operator.
They do not carry relatively large costs in construction, operation and maintenance of the network.
In the world this type of virtual operators are usually profiled with low costs - they offer cheap SMS calls and messages that however, it often counters with the offer of more adjusted services.
Thus, for example, Mobile Tesco in Britain offers at least half of cheap SMS with respect to competition.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it can also be a good blow to bet on a trivial target group.
This operator is specifically addressed to man.
"The right man chooses Mobilking - is the operator who likes and who can be trusted," says David Seibert, the CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, who works this virtual operator.
It's hard to say if it looks like the concept of Poland could catch up in our country.
The spokesman for Vodafone, Miroslav Čepický, therefore doubts: "The Czech market is relatively small to access by segments on which most virtual operators are based.
Moreover from the point of view of the supply of services is relatively saturated"
In the Czech Republic there are no possibilities, say mobile operators
However, it seems almost certain that if in the Czech Republic there will be any virtual operator that will not be Mobilking.
"We're talking about the expansion of this successful project, however, in Czech R. doesn't seem too hopeful.
Rather it is the launch of Mobilking in other countries in our region," he said in telephone conversation for mobile.cz, Jana Studničková, spokesperson for the Penta financial group.
Indirectly, he ensured that current mobile telephony operators in the Czech Republic definitely do not bow to this idea.
Rather, they try to do everything possible to avoid any potential competition.
Interested about the launch of a virtual mobile operator already shows it by the GTS Novera group that I would like to take a further step to become a real competition of Telefónica O2 in the field of business customers.
"We have a great interest in this, in order to offer our customers not only fixed telephony services but also mobile telephony.
And the sooner, the better.
With this possibility we have met repeatedly with all Czech mobile telephony operators.
With some of them we have been able to make progress at the meetings," said the group spokesperson, Pavel Kaidl.
Then maybe they'll shine better times.
It seems that, for non-official information, the first official operator would probably have to arrive by the end of the year.
But for now its appearance is accompanied by an impenetrable wall of silence.
"At the moment we believe that the situation is suitable for the emergence of a virtual operator in the Czech market.
The Czech market compared to others is a very specific market.
So far no one has been addressed to us with some complex and serious project in this field," he said for mobile.cz, Vlastimil Sršeň, spokesperson of Telefónica O2.
The specificity of the Czech market concerns other operators.
The T-mobile spokesman, Martina Kemrová, in exceptional accordance with O2's opinion, adds: "We have not yet registered any viable commercial projects that, bilaterally beneficial, can continue to develop."
And he adds: "On the T-Mobile network it will be difficult to find some virtual operator until the end of the year.
At this moment we should already have on the table some specific contract that would be possible to study on such short horizon"
Vodafone directs its attention rather than meeting the requirements of a 3G licence.
Miroslav Čepický adds: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, and this is about the distribution of expenditure and infrastructure.
We consider this precisely as the greatest input from the customers' point of view.
Vodafone's main strategy in this field is in the partner with whom to establish a shared network for a fast internet on mobile."
Responsible offices - with uña and meat operators
The progress of mobile operators can be easily understood, but the entry of another operator would mean increasing competition which would lead to a price drop and thereby a drop in profits.
Then why facilitate the entry to the competition?
When the operators want to get something, they are able to pull off the same rope, proof of it is the agron when U:phone came up.
Perhaps the biggest pressure on the ČTÚ was at the time of U:fon's entry by the T-Mobile society.
It testifies to the public information accessible on the websites of the ČTÚ.
But precisely now U:fon serves as an argument why not accept a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová adds this: "Evens, not long ago the competitive environment in the mobile telephony market was opened to a fourth operator.
With regard to the nature of the mobile telephony market in the Czech Republic, it is natural that another player's entry into the market would be for him and, above all, for his large requirements."
This is why this access to mobile operators is tremendously discouraging due to the absolute uninterest of the Czech regulator.
This is not just the position of the ČTU, which unfortunately has no competence to intervene in commercial tenders, unlike Britain and other developed countries.
This belongs purely to the Office for the Protection of Commercial Licensing (UOHS).
However, it expressed its typical stance on this issue.
"The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile telephony market would be possible after an agreement on the rental of the necessary infrastructure between a mobile telephony operator and a virtual operator was closed.
So far no agreement has been closed since the offer of potential stakeholders rather was not interesting enough for classical operators," added our question Kristian Chalupa, from the UOHS External Relations Department.
These statements do not surprise the representatives of the operators.
For the offices to represent the interests of consumers, this is more than a consideration, apart from that, they should observe that no one takes advantage of their position on the market.
Especially when Kristian Chalupa adds: "On the outside where virtual operators work normally we can observe that their entry into the market contributed to the price drop of mobile telephony services"
Of course, the pressure on the correct functioning of the market and price drop does not fall within the interest of UOHS.
