"The Office in this regard has not found signs of unfair competition and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators has a dominant position, therefore they do not have a corresponding rise in liability in their actions on the market.
The tools needed to open the mobile telephony market to virtual operators, rather, are missing, as well as telecommunications regulators," he added to his response Chalupa.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of the many conflicting points.
There is clearly a relevant market analysis developed by the ČTú that telecommunications is from the point of view of commercial tendering a single market.
In this type of market, of course, none of the Czech operators has a dominant position.
However, some of the legal experts offer another vision - for a virtual operator to emerge is always necessary to agree with the network administrator.
And the mobile telephony operator - with all his logic - has the monopoly of his network.
Therefore, in a particular segment it must be necessarily dominant.
And if this argument is not accepted, at least for UOHS should represent a warning the fact that three mobile operators ascend in a similar manner.
The current complaints from stakeholders (injured by GTS Novera) show that in all negotiations with operators they are collapsing with many similar impediments.
Loading responsibility in the ČTú is a fairly common trick in the field of telecommunications from which the UOHS washes its hands in all this matter.
We've already met with him in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, a new amendment to the telecommunications law was introduced recently to expand the competition of the ČTú in the field of trade tenders that did not take effect, even though a number of specialists promised that the situation would improve.
This should be well known by the representatives of UOHS, but it is clear that their interests are elsewhere.
It's all right, when nobody looks
At the same time, unavoidably it still works as well as a pseudoviral operator that on the Czech mobile telephone networks there already exist a few.
They are companies that put their own prices to mobile telephony services which, however, only one part are public.
These are usually companies that are engaged in multilevel marketing.
Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others offer their own mobile phone services.
Usually only a few elected get the price list of these companies.
The magic is that the company, with respect to the operator, acts as a classic business customer of the company in charge of a large number of SIM cards.
As a special customer you will later receive special prices and other offers.
The problem is that commercial conditions in all Czech mobile telephony operators prohibit this type of resale.
"If cases were discovered such as those cited could be referred to under the terms of contract that could be translated at the end of collaboration with the given society," he answered the question about this problem Martina Kemrová.
But it is quite unlikely that such activity by mobile telephone operators would not reach responsible people.
Precisely in the case of the three companies mentioned above, they can become thousands of customers.
None of the operators are against this procedure.
With the activities of these companies they gain nothing despicable and, at the same time - unlike the real virtual operators - in no way threaten their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický warns us of the possible problems: "the law allows such a speculation, however, the services of this company are only used by so many percent of customers.
