The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Choose the best
Listen to the four presentations of the new version of the Czech official anthem.
On Sunday, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek on the day of official Czech celebrations presented the new official recording of the hymn Where, my home.
The new anthem recorded it by the orchestra of the National Theatre under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
There are four versions available - two versions that are Solos, one by male voice and another by female voice, another by Coro and another instrumental.
Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka are responsible for the singing.
The authors of the anthem arrangements are Otakar Jeremiaš and Jaroslav Krček.
On the iHNed.cz server you can listen to the four versions.
Bělohlávek sees this Czech national song as one of the most beautiful hymns.
Czech Radio has already said before that it intentionally chose for solo singers with representative young voices that are more expressive and popular.
"From the beginning I tried with both of them and then, also, with the Choir that were fixed in the saying so that the text would be well understood, so that it would have consonance," he said.
The Czech official anthem celebrates next year on 175th anniversary.
The song Where, my home played for the first time in 1834 in the tables of the State Theatre in the original Czech work Fidlovačka by Josef Kajetán Tyl and arranged with the music of František Škroup.
It won popularity and people made it their own.
The first stanza of the song after the emergence of Czechoslovakia in 1918 became, naturally, a part of the official anthem.
One of the seven official symbols remained even after the emergence of the independent Czech Republic.
