Wednesday, October 1, 2008, is written in the history of the Prague Transportation Company the date on which the first passengers enter the subway, tram and bus with an electronic bonus in their pockets instead of a paper ticket.
This can now be purchased by nearly one hundred thousand people who own the Opencard chip card.
Passengers can buy the 30-day, 90-day bonus and the annual bonus (this will be valid as from 1 January 2009) and simultaneously upload it to their chip card at the infocentres and positions of the transport company at Metro stations, Muzeum, Městek, Nádraží Holešovice, Anděl, Roztyly, Letňany, Kobylisy, Rajská zahrada, Kačerov and Luka.
Bonuses can be purchased from yesterday's internet on the pages of the transport company, www.dpp.cz.
The service, until the afternoon, was used by more than four hundred people.
Those who start using the internet as a form of trade can definitely start to forget the ticket sales posts at the metro stations, where until now they have to make regular queues to take out a normal ticket.
The bonus is purchased on the Internet, and the Opencard card is recharged at one of the thirteen subsidiaries of the Municipal Library.
"In these places there is a window with trained staff that helps those interested in internet shopping and also with the recharging of the bonus purchased on your card," said project spokesman Martin Opatrný.
Apart from the library, it will also be possible to reload the e-bony in the Opencard on the automatic exponent machines found in some subway halls.
How are these exponent machines?
They are red, they remind us of a pick-up machine and travelers will probably have already set themselves up at the Roztyly metro stations, Budějovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská.
"Now there are five in the city, but at the end of the year there would have to be 80," Opatrný completed.
The bonus is controlled by the machine instead of the driver
The use of the machine, which will start working tomorrow, is simple.
Just enter the Opencard chip card into it and the bonus previously paid will be charged only on it.
The electronic bonds from tomorrow are valid not only in the capital but also in its surroundings.
In other words, in the roundabout trains and bus lines from numbers 300 to 499 that mainly use the inhabitants of central Bohemia.
"In the trains attached to the integrated transport of Prague there are reviewers equipped with a reader card that will help confirm the validity of the time and the bonus area," explained the ticket control, Filip Drápal of the organization Ropid, which establishes the schedule of the public transport of Prague.
Surrounding buses have their reader cards mounted on the driver's locker.
When entering it is necessary not only to show the card to the driver but also to accompany it with the Opencard at the place intended for it on the side of the box.
With this, the driver controls the validity of the bonus.
"If the passenger needs to verify the validity of the bonds there is nothing easier than asking the driver for this information," Drápal completed.
Passengers who do not travel on Circulation buses and do not remember when they are finished the bonus's validity can go to the outgoing machines where the cards are recharged.
Here, on the machine screen, you will be shown information about the validity of your document.
