The interview - Blood is safe again
Hema-Québec celebrated yesterday his 10th anniversary of his foundation, and his president, Francine Décary, was right to rejoice because Hema-Québec has once again been one of the safest and most effective blood providers in the world.
And above all, it regained the confidence of the public who had been seriously wavered by the blood scandal contaminated in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is known, national blood reserves administered by the Canadian Red Cross Blood Transfusion Service have been contaminated by the Human Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In the face of this drama and the discontent of the public, the Government of Canada conducted a public survey, chaired by Judge Horacio Krever, in February 1994, which intended to clarify the circumstances that had led to this tragedy and to make recommendations so that such a disaster could no longer be reproduced.
While Judge Krever was late in presenting his relationship, certain provinces then created a committee that had the objective of planning a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee carried out this mission.
As a result of Gélineau and Krever reports, two suppliers have been created in Canada: Hema-Québec to provide Quebec and the Canadian Blood Society to supply all other provinces and territories.
" In 1998, when Hema-Québec began its activities, almost 38% of people still had confidence in the blood system in Quebec, Décary recalls.
The situation was discouraging.
After making a lot of efforts to improve the safety of blood products and a lot of work during the years that followed, we have regained the confidence of the public ", he said before proudly saying that at the beginning of 2008, about 94 per cent of the Quebec population had the following confidence in Hema-Québec.
Dr. Décary recalls, however, that "trust is extremely fragile."
Since its creation on 28 September 1998, Hema-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At that time, we attended the birth in Europe of many cases of the human variant of mad cow disease, a new variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob's disease, says Décary.
And we didn't know if this disease could be transmitted by blood.
So we support one of the main recommendations of the reports of Krever and Gélineau, according to which when we do not know it and when a serious illness can emanate from that, in this case the disease of Creutzfeldt-Jakob that is characterized by a degeneration of the brain that inevitably leads to death, we introduce exclusion measures.
In April 1999, we denied the blood of people who had remained in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980.
But, a few years ago, it has been shown beyond doubt that this disease is transmitted by blood.
This episode showed us so that the precautionary principle that was applied had meaning."
In 1999 a much more sensitive HIV detection technique appeared on the market: the nucleid acid tests that enable the donors to directly detect the presence of the virus and not that of anti-virus antibodies, which have been based on the tests used so far.
Tests of nucleid acid allowed shortening the period between the moment the person has been infected and the time when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, explains the specialist.
We were able to reduce this period in less than a week.
We thus substantially reduce the risk that certain donors are infected without knowing it and that we cannot detect them.
These improvements allowed the risk of AIDS being significantly reduced by blood transfusion.
Today, one person every 12 million is at risk of receiving HIV-infected blood.
"That means that 12 million blood products will have to be distributed before someone is infected with HIV.
As Hema-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products each year, it will pass more than 24 years before a case of transmission of HIV comes through a blood product.
I believe that one can now receive or prescribe a blood transfusion to recover health without concern," says the head of Hema-Québec's management.
" Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the security of our products.
You never know which pathogen could emerge in the system.
Last year the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of the Meeting, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted by an insect in the blood.
It must be constantly vigilant ", Dr. Décary pursues before stressing that in addition to safe supplies, Hema-Québec must also provide for sufficient supplies.
" Needs are increasing because the population is aging.
Since more aggressive cancer treatments often require injection of red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also has consequences on the network of blood donors who regroup on average only 3% of Quebecers eligible for blood donation. "
All people with good health, aged 18 and who meet the eligibility criteria, however, can donate blood every 56 days, or six times a year.
On average, 14 % of the people who propose their blood are not accepted, because they suffer from AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they travel in a country where malaria reigns, they will be excluded for a period of one year.
" With this 3%, we managed to maintain an inventory covering the needs of hospitals.
The shortages are very rare.
But it is necessary to renew the members of this donor network as they age and can no longer give their blood.
But it is difficult to convince people to give their blood, but above all to hold them and encourage them to be regular donors.
Since present life is very unbridled, we rarely find the time to spend an hour to donate your blood," Francine Décary is distressed.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Hema-Québec supplies not only blood products, but also human tissues, including bone grafts, heart valves, eye balloons and skin that is almost exclusively used for large burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being stored in Hema-Québec, which also manages the only public blood bank of the umbilical cord in Quebec.
The umbilical cord that was formerly considered to be biomedical waste is filled with a rich blood of stem cells that can be used for the treatment of severe diseases such as leukemia.
" We have celebrated a few weeks ago, the placing on the bank of our thousandth sample of blood from the umbilical cord is expected to take more than a thousand of these a year.
We would have to start proposing it for grafts at the beginning of the next year, ", Dr. Décary needs that describes this cord blood-taking program as very popular.
" Many mothers are disappointed that they cannot enjoy this, since Hema-Québec has no resources to propose this complex and expensive program at all hospitals in Quebec.
