Psychology of overlaps: Why do we spend more money?
The auction participants are willing to spend more money and overvalue the product.
The neurologists and economists of the University of New York discovered the neurological - economic basis of this known and apparently irrational behavior.
According to the study in Science magazine, people do not want to lose in competitions like eBay auctions, so they prefer to pay even an excessive price.
Scientists tried to establish the neurological scheme of this "game" by means of experimental auctions.
One of the volunteer groups played lottery, the other participated in a auction and while under examination through the functional magnetic resonance imaging system (fMRI) the active brain areas of the individuals participating in the experiment.
In both games the participants could earn money, but during auctions, where it is a fundamental element to bet more than the other, by losing the game, the functioning of the complex called stratum located below the cerebral cortex was intensified.
This area of the brain, in addition to many other functions, plays a role in the mechanism of "auto prize" of the nervous system.
According to scientists, increased betting is explained as a prevention to avoid causing an intense reaction to the stratum.
To support his theory, the economists of the scientific group also carried out a financial follow-up study.
In this experiment three groups wagered against one person under different circumstances.
The control group was simply informed of the actual value of the product in question, and its members were betted.
Another group in addition to this was promised that if they won, they would receive $15 more prize.
On the other hand, the third group received exactly $15 before the auction, but in case of losing the auction, the group members lost even that money.
So the only difference between the two groups was that the triumph was highlighted for one and for the other the failure.
However, by testing the hypothesis of neurologists, the members of the group who played "against failure" were willing to bet even more than the members of the control group and the "gain" group.
"These results cannot be deducted from any previously existing economic theory.
Those so far explained the phenomena of auctions only with the joy of winning and risk prevention.
Only the visual neurological methods helped resolve this contradiction between the two theories, so that we now come to a third explanation" - established Andrew Schutter, professor of economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When should you go to the doctor?
Around five hundred million people in the world suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary chronic liver disease is considered one of the main causes of death.
The number of infections in this country is estimated at one hundred thousand, but only seven thousand receive treatment because many of the patients do not know they are infected.
Hepatitis is the common name for different liver diseases caused by viruses.
Symptoms are very similar; liver infection and jaundice are characteristic, but their pathogens and the diseases caused are very different.
Hepatitis viruses depending on the pathogen are propagated by two main forms: hepatitis A and E by food (e.g. by water or contaminated food), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses by blood and body moods (sperm, vagina humor, saliva).
It is recommended that travellers be protected by A and B virus vaccine, against C there are no vaccines.
Hepatitis A symptoms occur two or three weeks after eating the infected food, manifested by a general poor condition, weakness, abdominal pain and nausea.
After this appear in the skin and in the white of the eyes jaundice, excrement becomes clear, dark-coloured urine and healing may last even two - three weeks.
Annually, one million people die in cancer and liver cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B, the most serious forms of this disease.
The main reason for this is that, according to the calculations, only one in ten patients receives pharmacological treatment.
Hepatitis C may also have very serious consequences: without treatment it can produce liver cirrhosis and even cancer.
Most patients do not know that he is ill because this pathological agent slowly destroys the liver cells and often the first symptoms only appear 20-30 years later.
Premature recognition, systematic medical control is therefore very important.
This disease is much more common in three groups: people who had blood transfusion before 1991, drug users, and those who wear tattoos.
Currently, there are about 200 million people in the world suffering from chronic hepatitis C.
Since this disease can be discovered with routine laboratory control too, it is worth consulting with the family doctor when experiencing some unknown symptoms.
The disease has healing if it is discovered in time, it is possible to eradicate the virus from the body, so you can suppress the infection and prevent cancer.
On 30 September is the World Hepatitis Day, which was organized for the first time in 2004 by organizations representing the sick.
Its objective is to draw attention to the causes of chronic liver infections caused by viruses and the importance of their early recognition.
Does it hurt less who they believe in God?
According to a recent research, religious faith has a calming effect that also alleviated the death of martyrs of Catholicism.
Scientists at Oxford University conducted an interesting experiment: they analyzed that religious belief in how it influences human pain - reported the British Telegraph newspaper.
Within the framework of this unique experiment, 12 Catholic believers and the same number of atheists applied electric shock, while everyone was watching a painting of the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to exclude most of their pain.
Thanks to the scanning technique of the human brain, it was found that Catholic believers were able to activate that part of their brain that is responsible for the regulation of pain.
This experiment is the first of the series of research in which scientists, philosophers and theologians from the various departments of the University also participate.
The analysis took place as follows; they set a striking instrument to the left hand of the patient, which applied the electric shock.
The researchers asked the participants of the experiment to set their eyes on two paintings; the Virgin Mary, a work of 17th century Sassoferrato and the Lady of Leonardo da Vinci's armory of the 15th century.
The researchers had the hope that the spectacle of the Virgin Mary would give rise to a certain religious spirit among the faithful, while they chose Leonardo's oil because it was not too different from the other, and they thought it had a reassuring effect.
Patients spent half an hour in an MRI scanner, receiving 20 electrical shocks in four successive parts while observing the religious theme painting or the other.
The Catholics said that when they looked at the Virgin Mary they felt in "security" as "protected" people, "they calmed down and in their heart the peace reigned."
Observing the religious theme picture felt 12 percent less pain than when they watched Leonardo's work.
Psychologist Miguel Farias who also participated in the experiment, thinks that with any image so striking you can achieve a similar effect with atheists as well, you just have to find the right image.
"We should find the portrait of a person for whom they feel very positively, like by a mother or a father," said the psychologist.
