The intelligent car imitates the flight of the beehive
What would be the best way to develop technologies in order to avoid collisions, if not the imitation of the obstacles sensors existing in nature?
For example, that of bees.
In a surprising project presented at CEATEC in Japan, bees gave the starting point for Nissan engineers to design the next generation of the collision prevention system.
The Nissan, in cooperation with the University of Tokyo, designed the robotic system of type BR23C automobiles mimicking nature, to which the characteristics of bees were given, with the ultimate aim of creating a system that can do away with all collisions.
During the flight each beehorro creates its own ovaled private space that actually looks very similar to our safety protective capsule - explained in the Kazuhiro Doi exhibition, technological director of RP and development and research.
They play an important role in the eyes composed of bees that are able to see in all directions at an angle greater than 300 degrees.
To copy the function of the composite eyes, engineers used the laser beam length measurement system.
It identifies the obstacles in front of the BR23C within a distance of 2 metres, at an angle of 180 degrees, calculates its distance and sends a signal to the vehicle microprocessor that immediately turns into a maneuver to avoid collision.
In a fraction of seconds the obstacle is identified, then the vehicle robot imitating the movements of the bees, modifies the direction turning to the necessary extent the wheels.
Unlike any existing system, this maneuver is completely instinctive.
"If not so, the robot of the vehicle could not react quickly enough to avoid obstacles" - explains Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Laboratory and the project of the vehicle robot.
It must react immediately and instinctively, as this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable inner layer of the protective safety capsule, in a layer within which all types of collisions are currently considered inevitable.
The whole process must reflect what a bee does to do away with other bees.
This process must be done in an open and close the eyes.
However, unlike the bees, the movement cannot turn up, down or diagonally, but can only be two-dimensional and exclusively in the turn direction of the wheels
In this way, instead of the infinite possibilities that exist for bees to dodge other bees, here they only used as a possibility for the robot of the car the rotating movement and the acceleration besides the braking.
BR23C uses lithium-polymer batteries that are lighter and their energy density is greater, which means that they have a longer life span than lithium-ion.
According to Andoh, the important thing is the instinctive and intelligent reaction and not the data processing capacity, much less the storage capacity.
This device in each second must only process some input signals and react as the case may be.
There is no need to store this data or react with an instinctive logic based on data from previous maneuvers, so it uses only a few tens of kilobytes of memory.
No memory of gigabytes, no megabytes.
This is the first step in developing technology to immediately avoid obstacles, which according to Nissan's calculations, can be incorporated into the models manufactured in series within ten years.
Another possibility for its application is to incorporate the unit into the GPS satellite navigation system to lead the driver to his destination, avoiding the obstacles on his way.
