Industrial prices continue to rise
In August 2008, national industrial selling prices increased by 0.1 percent compared to last month's prices and by 12.9 percent compared to August 2007 prices - reported the Central Statistical Office (KSH).
Industrial export prices rose by 1.1 per cent compared to July 2008 and decreased by 3.9 per cent compared to the previous year.
And as a result of changes in domestic and export prices, industrial production prices increased by 0.7 per cent compared to the previous month and by 3.2 per cent compared to the previous year.
Industrial sales prices increased only to a minimum, with 0.1 percent.
The domestic sales prices of the processing industry sectors rose at a minimum of 0.1 per cent compared to the month of July.
The higher price increase occurred in August 2008, in the leather and footwear production sector (2.8 percent), due primarily to the increase of 4.6 percent per month in bags and belts and the increase of 2.5 per cent in footwear.
The higher price level of plastic and chemical base materials resulted in a significant monthly increase in the production branch prices of chemicals (1.6 percent).
There was a decrease in price in the petrochemical sector, (1.4 per cent), in the production of electrical machinery and instruments (0.9 per cent), as well as - to a minimum extent - in the processing sectors of wood (0.1 per cent).
The prices of paper manufacture, editorials and printing prices did not change.
In the rest of the processing industry, there was an increase in prices between 0.2 and 0.9 per cent.
In the supply of electricity, gas, heat and water that represent an important weight within domestic trade, an increase of 0.3 per cent was recorded in August, first as a result of the effect of the increase in official prices from the first of July.
In a comparison of a twelve-month period - in domestic sales of the processing industry sectors - the highest price increase was recorded in the petrochemical sector (32.4 percent).
In the metal processing sector, an increase of 13.2 per cent was observed, while in the food, drink and tobacco industry, of determining weight, there was an increase of 11 per cent.
There was a decrease in prices in the textile industry (2.5 per cent), as well as in the manufacture of electrical machinery and instruments (0.3 per cent).
In the rest of the processing sectors, the rate of price growth was between 0.6 and 9.1 percent.
Over the past year in the processing industry globally increased prices by 10.2 percent.
The electricity prices, the supply of gas, heat and water exceeded the prices of the previous year by 18.7 percent.
In August, among the different sectors of domestic trade, the largest monthly price increase (0.7 per cent) was recorded in the investment goods sectors.
In the consumer goods sectors, prices increased by 0.3 per cent, in energy and intermediate sectors prices there was no change compared to the previous month.
In August 2008, with regard to the same month of the previous year, the higher price increases occurred in the energy sectors and in the intermediate industry (16.8 percent).
In the consumer product branches, a 6.8 percent decrease was recorded and in investment goods 1.4 percent.
The export prices of the industry calculated in HUF increased by 1.1 per cent compared to the previous month, and compared to 12 months, there was a decrease of 3.9 per cent.
The contribution of our national currency in one month was reduced by 1.7 percent over the euro and by 7.1 percent over the dollar, compared to August 2007 strengthened by 7.5 percent over the euro and 15.9 percent over the dollar.
