According to the European Parliament, there is a need for a broad consensus on these issues, both among Gypsies and among non-Gypsians.
As soon as the school starts, a Roma student will have more opportunities to become an active member of the labour market; through income and consumer taxes they will also contribute to the national budget.
"The Gypsies, as citizens of the European Union, must ensure the right to a quality education and ensure the abolition of secret and low-level education," said Lívia Jóroka.
According to the European Parliament, the objective and active unity of the European Union is necessary to speed up the process of school segregation immediately, so it is of fundamental importance that the existing and planned anti-discrimination directives are properly complied with.
"The vicious circle of poverty, segregation and unemployment must be broken, and it must be offered to Roma children the possibility of guaranteeing democratic space so that they can contribute to the future of Europe as citizens of full rights," Jóroka demanded.
The aim of the European Summit for Equal Opportunities organized annually since last year's Berlin meeting, which was held in the sign of the European Year of Equal Opportunities, is to ensure a unique forum to promote the abolition of discrimination and equal opportunities at European and national level in the Member States.
